caption: Food that i would recommend for this location : Mao's pork belly, spicy dice chicken, big plate chicken which is really big portion which come with noodle, grilled lamb foreshank and their mini grilled fish. Can try their lamb chop and grilled beef ribs which is a little bit cozy. Spicy pork wonton and  Chong pork dumpling are not bad too. Cold dish i used to have their shredded potato and cucumber salad. Tried the above stuff since the lockdown. Overall not too bad.
Best authentic Chinese in the area
The food and service were ahead of my expectations. I really loved the atmosphere of this place. Extraordinary spot to take my family out for dinner.

I ordered NY restaurant week menu (vegetable dry pot and sweet and sour chicken) which was great!!  I’m very impressed with the dry pot! Very authentic but not so spicy. The set came with appetizer, dessert and a drink! Definitely a good deal 👍

Ordered Yu kitchen spicy chicken with noodles, szechuan spicy wonton noodle soup, and got a free lamb shank (s) as part of a promotion. Loved all the dishes. Specially the chicken! Comes wih potato, some onion and bell pepper. Very tasty, a bit spicy (but ordered mild and it wasnt that spicy). Paid $40 (lamb shank was free from promo) and had enough for 4 people, so not a bad deal at all! Restaurant has small hand wipes and candy. Service was very fast (order ready before expected time). Will repeat again.

Hands down the best general tso's chicken I've had, and I've had a lot. Their dried hot pot is pretty good (a little too salty), and their food is always a bit less greasy than the usual chinese takeout spots. Highly recommend.
Food is tasty and not too expensive.

This place is small, comfortable, and serves the best made authentic Chinese food in the north end of UWS (yes I took into account DH, SG, Atlas, Han Dynasty, HHH, Grain House, Dumpling Room, and that new fancy noodle place whose name I can't recall. I exclude 108 DHP, it serves a different type of food). The chef/owner is passionate, some of their ingredients came straight from China, and they are incredibly affordable. This place is so good I want to move into their building. Selection can be limited after you have been there hundreds of time. I suggest they come up with some seasonal selections!
Food was mediocre but service wasn’t good.

Legit! A little pricey but worth it. For example, the dumpling skins are just thin enough to avoid breaking, but this enough to not feel doughy. Also, there's little high end touches like the dishes, tea, etc.

We were the only customers in the restaurant, yet the waiter was very unwelcoming and rushing us to finish our food and leave with rude behavior. When we refused to leave a tip for bad service he started cursing at us. Definitely a place to avoid.

It's rare for a single place to offer such a variety of authentic regional food from Northwestern and Western China. The qualitily is good enough for developing a taste for these food, at least for the ones that we tried.

This place was...disappointing at best. Their menu was confusing and had almost no organization and their dishes had no description. I ordered the xinjiang chicken, bok choy sauteed with garlic, and wontons in hot sour soup. Everything came out looking really good, but it didn't taste as good as it looked. The chicken came doused in pepper oil. I can handle spice really well and this was a little hard for me. At the end of the meal, my lips and tongue were unpleasantly tingly and numb. The wontons were not fresh at all and the broth was horrendous. It was just spicy salt water with A TON of pepper. Out of the three dishes I ordered, only the bok choy was good, and it's really hard to screw up that kind of dish.

Went to dinner last night there, the food was awesome.. it is not easy to fine authentic Szechuan flavor in this neck of wood.. their grill lamb foreshanke was amazing.. if you are looking for some great tasting Chinese food, drop by and have a taste and you won't regret it.
GREAT FOOD

This Sichuan restaurant is fair and has a good taste. It is my favorite.  A few days ago, I also packed a shredded cabbage, beef spicy, seafood spicy, Xinjiang chicken cold dishes to the state park to share with friends, a beautiful day.

This place is located a block away from the nearest Xian Famous Foods on the UWS. Great place to go to if you are craving a little more that just Chinese noodles. They have a healthy selection of Chinese dishes that are reminiscent of restaurants found in China. The cucumber dish and the eggplant dish were delicious. I hope to go back again to try the whole fish dishes. Staff was very nice and the taste of the food was very good. If you are searching for an "authentic Chinese taste" on the Upper West Side. Check this place out.

Quick service, friendly staffs, and clean restaurant. When I first saw this place, I thought this would be a great place to enjoy good-priced Chinese food. However, after taking a bite of their honey sesame chicken, I realized that the meat was not fresh, and the sauce was too overwhelming. I also tried their beef hot pot and beef soup noodles, but everything was average at best. If I were to try here again, I would not go for meat dishes but try their rice dishes instead.

Nice food! This store has limited sits available. However, the food here is authentic. We got the cauliflower, the roasted lamb leg and the beef with tofu. I wasn’t expected ground beef in the beef with tofu but the flavor of it was good so no complaints. The price was a little high for each dish, but they have promotions for a one dollar lamb leg that make things up. Overall a good restaurant!

Something different. Its so refreshing to go to an asian restaurant not catering to the chicken and broccoli crowd.  I ordered cumin lamb here. ($15.75) a bit expensive i thought until i saw the pile of food they give you. The portion is huge.  I ordered medium spicey which was right.  The lamb was delicious. I also ordered the spicey potato salad.  Excellent as well although only mildly spicey.  Not a great vegetable selection here but the menu was bigger than expected.

AVOID AT ALL COSTS. I had one of the worst "food ripoffs" I've ever experienced. The place is beautiful looking, and to start, I wanted to try the "Sliced Chicken with Sesame Chili Oil" for $7.50 + tax. I could not wait to get my dish, thinking how great it would be. I got a small plate of THE CHEAPEST, MOST DISGUSTING diced pieces of BOILED chicken (the way they do it in the $1 places in Chinatown for soup broth), and HALF of these little pieces were cartilage and bone. I was furious. I went up to the counter, put my plate and tray by the register, and told the guy "That I paid $8 for 80 cents worth of boiled chicken is a travesty. You should be ashamed.". Of course he just gave me a blank stare. Goodbye crooks
